References: <c13523ef-b1c2-1e4d-c084-9e232eeb819b@psychologie.uni-heidelberg.de>
Message-ID: <9d4ddef4-6796-c41b-14a3-edf765564a07@imbi.uni-freiburg.de>

Dear Anna-Lena,

I would suggest that you have a look at R?cker et al. (2017) as well as 
sections 16.5.4 and 16.5.5 of the Cochrane Handbook 
(https://handbook-5-1.cochrane.org/).

These papers deal with multiple treatment groups, however, the same 
arguments apply if you have different age groups etc. within a study.

In summary, it is fine to include multiple independent groups from a 
study under a fixed effect model. However, you should combine the groups 
within a study under the random effects model.

Best wishes, Guido

Reference:
R?cker G, Cates CJ, Schwarzer G. Methods for including information from 
multi-arm trials in pairwise meta-analysis. Res Synth Methods. 
2017;8(4):392?403.


From wolfg@ng@viechtb@uer @ending from m@@@trichtuniver@ity@nl  Thu Dec 13 15:24:13 2018
From: wolfg@ng@viechtb@uer @ending from m@@@trichtuniver@ity@nl (Viechtbauer, Wolfgang (SP))
